## Workflow Sequence

Follow this order:

1. initialize the canonical inventory before returning or rejecting any table;
2. discover source surfaces for the current source type and record every discovery query or navigation surface;
3. build product_type_sex_worklist for product-scoped source types when requested product types exist;
4. close selected source boundaries according to Source Boundary Closure;
5. enumerate every concrete size-chart table reachable inside each opened bounded surface;
6. apply market selection before writing final table states;
7. write selected concrete tables only to table_list with state accepted, and write every non-returned concrete table to table_list with state duplicate, equivalent, market_conflict, market_filtered, or rejected;
8. write SourceDiscoveryDeltaResult only after the canonical inventory is complete for the current attempt.

## Source Boundary Closure

Search pages, navigation pages, home pages, sitemap pages, FAQ index pages, help index pages, and other helper surfaces are discovery surfaces. Every concrete URL selected as a possible source boundary for this source type must be closed in the canonical inventory before handoff. A closed URL is one url_list entry with state opened and observed size-chart/table result evidence, or state rejected with a concrete rejection reason and evidence. Selected helper surfaces must be recorded as opened or rejected URL inventory entries with evidence and reasons. Do not leave selected seller/store/product URLs only inside broad URL evidence artifacts, notes, or verifier feedback. This includes selected helper surfaces and official or authorized seller/store roots surfaced by browser search evidence, such as marketplace store URLs. Do not put broad search-result or category product URL inventories in state.json. If you collect broad product URL lists for sampling or coverage, save them as separate evidence artifacts and reference those artifacts from discovery_query_list or url_list through evidence_path_list with the sampling or rejection rule in reason.

Do not exhaustively open every similar product URL from search or category results. For product-scoped source types, select the smallest browser-visible representative set needed to test the current requested product type inside each marketplace, seller, or store boundary: normally one official seller product per boundary unless evidence shows distinct size-chart mechanics. Record the sampling rule and store unselected broad result URLs only in separate evidence artifacts, not in state.json.

For product-scoped source types, product_type_sex_worklist is the source-discovery worklist. Start from the closed source-discovery sex set: women, men, girls, boys, unisex, and unisex_child. If the requested product type names an explicit sex, keep only that sex. If the requested product type does not name an explicit sex, create one worklist row for every sex in the closed set. A removed product type and sex row must remain in product_type_sex_worklist with state='rejected', reason and evidence_path_list that prove the pair is impossible for this product type. Worklist rows that still need source coverage use state='active'. Link URL entries, accepted tables, and market-filtered tables to the active worklist rows they close through worklist_key_list. Duplicate and equivalent table rows are audit/completeness rows only; they do not close active worklist rows, and the accepted table row they duplicate or equal must list every covered worklist_key.

When this source type uses official brand sources, identify browser-visible official host variants before concluding that the source type has no tables. Host variants include global brand domains, country-code brand domains, and locale paths that browser evidence shows as brand-owned. Open relevant official host roots and inspect visible navigation, footer, search, help, FAQ, sitemap, and static-page links. Do not stop after one official domain variant fails when another brand-owned host variant is visible or inferable from browser-visible evidence.

For each discovered official host, infer the browser-visible language and market from the opened page itself, then derive localized size-chart search-term families for that language and market. Use those localized search-term families through the runtime source-access contract, the site's own search, visible navigation, footer/help pages, and sitemap pages. Run separate searches for each distinct localized size-chart search-term family before concluding that no official size-guide table exists; these terms are search terms, not URL templates. Record the localized queries and the opened or rejected target source URLs in url_list. Do not conclude that an official host has no size guide until localized size-chart term searches for that host are represented in the canonical inventory.

Apply one market-selection ladder for accepted table rows. First search for the priority country code from PromptScope. If priority country tables exist for this source type, accepted table rows must contain only items whose country_code_list contains that priority country code. If no priority country table exists, accept global tables only when global tables exist and mark them with country_code_list=['GLOBAL']. If neither priority country nor global tables exist, accept European country tables only after verifying that the relevant official European country tables do not differ; mark such verified consensus rows with country_code_list=['EU']. If European country tables differ, record evidence-backed concrete table conflict entries only in table_list with state market_conflict, naming the exact conflicting country codes, URLs, and size_group_key values, do not encode the conflict as a terminal no-table reason, do not record the conflict in url_list, do not use it to close active worklist rows, and do not pick one locale.

After applying the market-selection ladder, write selected concrete tables to table_list with state accepted. Write every discovered concrete table that is not accepted after deduplication, equivalence checks, market conflict, market selection, or rejection to table_list with current evidence, state duplicate, equivalent, market_conflict, market_filtered, or rejected, and a table-specific reason.

## Retry And Recovery

On retry, read Previous stage result path and state.json when existing files are present. Preserve evidence-backed accepted candidates from those current files unless verification feedback identifies a concrete error in that candidate. Complete the missing bounded inventory, rejection reasons, or coverage around those candidates instead of discarding them.

## Terminal Handoff

Accept every unique size-chart source candidate backed by evidence files. One accepted table row represents one concrete size chart table, not one page. If one page contains multiple size chart tables with different size_group_key values, write one accepted table_list row per table. Inside one source type, accept at most one table row for one size_group_key; when another page, locale, or asset exposes a non-returned table for the same size_group_key, a rejected lower-priority market, or a conflicting European market, record that table in table_list with state duplicate, equivalent, market_conflict, market_filtered, or rejected, current evidence paths, and a table-specific reason, but do not accept a second row with the same size_group_key.

One opened browser surface includes all size-chart content reachable from that surface without leaving its authority boundary: tabs, accordions, modals, popovers, rendered widgets, linked PDF or image assets, product-linked standard-size panels, help/FAQ answers, and Q&A panels. After opening such a surface, enumerate every browser-visible concrete size-chart table on that surface before handoff. Do not stop after the table that matches the product type or link that led to the surface.

For tabbed or grouped size-chart surfaces, the canonical inventory table_list must contain one explicit entry for every visible table group and subtable in every opened tab. Returned tables use state accepted. Non-returned tables use state duplicate, equivalent, market_conflict, market_filtered, or rejected. If a visible table is duplicate or equivalent, name the returned size_group_key it maps to and record the evidence-backed reason. If it is market_conflict, market_filtered, or rejected, record the evidence-backed conflict, market-selection, or rejection reason. Do not use vague notes such as prior evidence, already discovered, or retained candidate instead of current evidence paths and table-specific non-returned reasoning.

Do not create one source candidate from product category, product title, variant labels, or option labels alone. source_title is the browser-visible chart group or table heading on the opened source surface. size_group_key is the normalized table key derived from source_title and evidence through the Size Group Key Contract. If an opened product page belongs to socks but its visible size-chart modal only exposes an Ayakkabi table, return the visible shoes table with the normalized shoes size_group_key or reject the socks candidate with an explicit inventory reason instead of inventing women_socks.

Requested product types are source-discovery worklist inputs for product-scoped source types and coverage targets for the later coverage_decide stage. They must not filter or narrow accepted table_list entries or table extraction scope. When an opened source page contains concrete tables that are outside the requested product types, still accept those tables. If requested product types are present, search for every requested product type in this source type. Do not encode product-type coverage in SourceDiscoveryDeltaResult; coverage_decide owns product-type coverage decisions.

If at least one concrete table candidate is evidence-backed, write it as an accepted table_list row even when some requested product types remain uncovered. Do not write product-type coverage gaps to source-discovery no-table reasons; coverage_decide owns uncovered requested product types.

Respect the source type boundary exactly; do not accept product-page measurement sections for official_brand_size_guide. SourceDiscoveryDeltaResult must contain only browsing_error_list. If no concrete table can be accepted after browser-backed inventory, write detailed no-table reasons as evidence-backed terminal entries in state.json so this source type is recorded as skipped/no-table and the workflow can continue to the next source type. Do not invent candidates.

